As of 2023-03, creating wiki (git) repositories on GitHub programmatically is not officially supported.

GitHub&#39;s official REST API (Version: 2022-11-28) supports the [creation of repositories](https://docs.github.com/en/rest/repos/repos?apiVersion=2022-11-28#create-a-repository-for-the-authenticated-user). However, if you try to create a &quot;wiki&quot; for some code repository, named say &quot;REPOSITORY_NAME&quot; (meaning, you want to create the git repository &quot;REPOSITORY_NAME.wiki&quot;), will end up with an error like:

```
{
  &quot;message&quot;: &quot;Repository creation failed.&quot;,
  &quot;errors&quot;: [
    {
      &quot;resource&quot;: &quot;Repository&quot;,
      &quot;code&quot;: &quot;custom&quot;,
      &quot;field&quot;: &quot;name&quot;,
      &quot;message&quot;: &quot;name cannot end in .wiki&quot;
    }
  ],
  &quot;documentation_url&quot;: &quot;https://docs.github.com/rest/reference/repos#create-a-repository-for-the-authenticated-user&quot;
}
gh: Repository creation failed. (HTTP 422)
```

AFAIK then, your only chance is to create the wiki repository using the non-documented call from the GitHub website: 

* On your browser, if you want to create a wiki manually, you will see that this is a call to a `GET` method with the URL pattern: `https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/REPOSITORY_NAME/wiki/_new`. This redirects you to a new site with the title &quot;Create new page&quot;.
* Inspecting the button `Save page` (id: `gollum-editor-submit`) shows you that the underlying routine to create a wiki git repository is a POST method with the pattern `https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/REPOSITORY_NAME/wiki` (the web HTML includes a hidden `input` with the name `authenticity_token`; again this is not documented and is likely to change). Calling this method with the right inputs (and I guess some needed headers) will create your desired new git repository. 
* Finally, to later push your git repository from scratch, you will need to force it: `git push -f origin`.

